===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|厃|卩|t1=person on a cliff or mountain|t2=kneeling person|ls=ic}}.

Written like {{zh-l|*𡴲}} during the {{w|Warring States period}}, an {{Han compound|人|山|t1=person|t2=mountain|ls=ic|nocap=y}}.

===Etymology===
Starostin reconstructs {{inh|zh|sit-pro||*ŋō̆j (~-ō̆l)|high, rise}} and compares [[危]] to {{cog|my|ငွား|t=be large, great, be high, to project prominently above and beyond others}}, {{cog|kac|tr=ŋoi|t=to rise, as a hill}}; & possibly {{w|Kiranti languages|Proto-Kiranti}} *''ŋo-''.

{{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} notes that Chinese and Written Burmese can be reconciled by assuming an ST final *''-l''; furthermore, {{och-l|危|tr=*ŋoi}} may be a vocalic variant of {{och-l|巍|tr=*ŋui}}, which in turn is related to {{och-l|魏|tr=*ŋuih}}.

